<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-698-228  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 698 228.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  July 23 1990 v7 n28 p9(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tektronix revamps its line of color X windows terminals. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Tektronix Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    TEK.andO;Product:   Tektronix TekXpress (Computer terminal) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     TerminalsX Windows (Standard)Product Introduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Text retrieval system combs through data, can overlap text fieldsandM;WATERLOO, Ontario -- Open Text Systems has released an ASCII text retrievalsystem that can sift through overlapping text fields, according to companyofficials.andM;The PAT ASCII text retrieval software is written in C and has been ported toVMS and Unix systems, including Ultrix and Xenix, according to David Terry,Open Text Systems' marketing director.andM;The system can search an entire database, or a specified subregion, which cancan be defined at run time and can nest and overlap in unrestrictedcombination, Terry said.andM;The PAT ASCII text retreival system was designed for use by the producers ofthe second edition of the Oxford English Dictionary (OED).andM;The second edition was released last year and contains more than 60 millionwords, according to Terry.andM;Researchers at the University of Waterloo's Centre for the New Oxford EnglishDictionary worked with Clarendon Press to devise software for integrating theOED's first edition, published in 1928, with subsequent revisions, accordingto Terry.andM;Open Text Systems was founded by researchers at the center.andM;The PAT retrieval system was developed around the OED, but it also has moregeneral applications, Terry said.andP;  &quot;The OED provided an excellent, complextest bed.andP;  The product is suited to general ASCII text processing, though ithas obvious applications in education,&quot; he said.andM;The product's core system is the PAT search and retrieval system, whichconducts infinite, or prefix, string searches, as opposed to simple wordsearches, according to Terry.andM;PAT has been timed to search the OED's 400MB database for matches to anyarbitrary string in less than a second on a Sun-3/160 system, Terry said.andM;PAT supports index points for each character in a database, as well asarbitrary stopwords and character mappings, according to Terry.andM;PAT can also conduct proximity, Boolean and set-algebraic searches, he said.andM;Open Text's text display module, Lector, furnishes users with views of thesearched text that resemble the original document, according to Terry.andM;&quot;PAT sends a character string to Lector, which tags it with text and typeinformation and display formats,&quot; he said.andM;Lector is designed for real-time display of tagged text on high-resolutionworkstations, according to Terry.andM;Open Text Systems also markets a translation tool kit for converting storedtext from one format to another, according to Terry.andM;The Transaction Toolkit uses standard grammars to convert text filesautomatically, he said.andP;  &quot;[The tool kit] reads input against output and makesthe appropriate conversions,&quot; he said.andM;PAT, Lector and the Transduction Toolkit are available now and are pricedfrom $10,000 to $40,000 per module, depending upon CPU.andM;Open Text Systems Inc. is located at Unit 622, Waterloo Town Square,Waterloo, Ontario, Canada N2J 1P2, (519) 746-3255.andO;</TEXT></DOC>